The paper discusses the defects of the Mersenne Twister as a pseudorandom number generator, which falls under the category of cryptography (cs.CR) and probability (cs.PR). It also discusses the memory requirements and implementation issues, which are related to data structures (cs.DS) and programming languages (cs.PL). Finally, it provides guidance for language implementors, which falls under software engineering (cs.SE).
